3) Composition operators (now tensor-aware)

Scalar tokens

Just A, C, etc.

Vector (ordered list)

‚ü®A, C, R‚ü©
Use when order matters but it‚Äôs still one unit.

Matrix (2D grid)

[ [F, E], [S, R] ]
Two axes (e.g., Frame√óEvidence, Safety√óReversibility).

Tensor (N-D)

ùïã(axes={time, frame, risk}, data=...)
Meaning is multi-axis; not reducible to one ordering.

Contraction (reduce along an axis)

contract(ùïã, axis=risk, op=max)
Example: ‚Äútake worst-case risk over scenarios.‚Äù

Projection (slice an axis)

proj(ùïã, frame=legal)
Evaluate under one frame.

This is how you avoid ‚Äúmatrix thinking‚Äù when the system is truly multi-dimensional.

‚∏ª

4) Semantics: compile rules updated for tensors

An expression compiles into a Decision Tensor Packet (DTP):
	‚Ä¢	intent
	‚Ä¢	invariants
	‚Ä¢	permissions
	‚Ä¢	tests
	‚Ä¢	exit
	‚Ä¢	trace
	‚Ä¢	axes (optional)
	‚Ä¢	aggregation (how to collapse tensor ‚Üí decision)

Default tensor aggregation rule

If a tensor is present and no aggregation is specified:

Safety-first aggregation:
contract(ùïã, axis=risk, op=max) then gate with S.

In plain terms: treat unknowns as multi-scenario; decide by worst-case safety unless overridden.

